To format small chunks of source code within a line of normal text, use the <code> tag. For example:

function <code>int m2()</code> is nice.

For syntax highlighting in source code, use the <syntaxhighlight> tag. For example, in C++:

<syntaxhighlight lang="cpp">
#include <iostream>
int m2 (int ax, char *p_ax) {
  std::cout <<"Hello World!";
  return 0;
}</syntaxhighlight>

To use special characters in text, you can often use numeric character references or character entity references. For example, &Agrave; and &#xC0; both render À (A-grave).

For diacritic marks, use character entity references. For example:

&Agrave; &Aacute; &Acirc; &Atilde; &Auml; &Aring; &AElig;

&Ccedil; &Egrave; &Eacute; &Ecirc; &Euml;

&Igrave; &Iacute; &Icirc; &Iuml; &Ntilde;

&Ograve; &Oacute; &Ocirc; &Otilde; &Ouml; &Oslash; &OElig;

&Ugrave; &Uacute; &Ucirc; &Uuml; &Yuml; &szlig;

